When my youngest son and his fiancee brought me here yesterday for Lunch...
I thought to myself as I walked in.... "I've been here before... but when?".
They tried to bring me here last year when I was visiting, but Archi's Thai was closed that day...
They took me to another place... and was extremely disappointed.
As you can see by the rating, Archi's was a pleasant surprise and very good Thai cuisine... judging by the Lunch Specials.
As I told the kids... Archi's is deserving of 5-Stars for the sampling of the Lunch Special... and if the Dinners were as good and consistent as the Lunch Special that I had.
Atmosphere is most unlike Southeastern Asian....
The decor is set in medium dark woods... furniture is French Provincial in style... pictures are, surprisingly, of Thailands French Colonial days with framed pictures of their former Royalty in Thailand of days gone by.
You will be surprised by this atmosphere... a little of French Colonial in an Asian restaurant.
On the menu....  Tom Yum Soup (**** Complimentary) Lemongrass, Lime Leaves and Blue Ginger infused Broth, Mushrooms, Tomatoes and Lime Juice... sprinkled with Cilantro and Green Onions.
For a smallish 3" diameter cup / bowl... this Soup could be considered Thailand's version of Chinese Hot and Sour Soup.
Dang good... but left me wanting more... but it's complimentary.
Lunch Special #4 - Red Curry Dish with Beef (***** $6.95 Shrimp-$7.95) Fresh Red Curry Paste in Coconut Milk with Zucchini, Bamboo Shoots (a lot of 'em), Basil, and Bell Peppers.
When you order this... the wait-staff will ask you the degree of Hot-ness that you want your Soup (from 1 to 10... with 1 being a lack of Heat and 10 being Super Hot)...
I was considering ordering the Soup with a 10... My son and his fiancee looked at me quizzically or amazingly.
They really tried to convince me to reconsider....
I tried this tactic...
I asked the waitress... "If you ordered this, what number would you order?
" She replied with a 6.
So, I compromised.... 8.
When the Soup came out, The Soup was accompanied by a very small Green Salad which was totally inconsequential considering it's size; a Thai Egg Roll (***)...
I really don't like totally Veggie Egg Rolls, and a thinly fried Won-Ton (****).
This was just a small sampling of from their extensive menu.
The Red Curry Soup was something else altogether... As you travel West across SouthEast Asia... you'll notice that the Asian countries will be more influence by Indian Cuisine as you travel.
This Soup was silky smooth from the Coconut Milk and the Red Curry gave it a warm color and unique flavor that only Curry can impose.
Coconut based Soups are some of my very favorite.
If I had to penalize the Soup for any reason, it would be for the amount of Bamboo Shoots... just too much.
Otherwise, something you should try whether it be a Lunch Special or at Dinner.
Lunch Special #5 - Spicy Basil Dish with Beef (***** $6.95) Stir Fried with Zucchini, Bell Peppers, Garlic, Chili and Fresh Basil.
This was a sampling that my son's fiancee obligingly gave me to try.
A very delicious Stir-Fry with Ground Beef.
I will try this next time... whenever that may be.
Wait-Staff was very friendly, helpful.
I asked the waitress how the smallish chain came to be named Archi's... She said Archi was the nickname of the owner, who started his restaurants seven years ago.
This location started up two years ago taking over a Pick-Up-Stix franchise that went bust.
She also said the owner usually is at the Rainbow location ( http://www.yelp.com/biz/archis-thai-kitchen-and-thai-bistro-las-vegas ) since that was the original restaurant and is quite larger in size.
One other advantage of this location is the proximity to my favorite Cinema in Las Vegas... the Regal Village Square 18 ( http://www.yelp.com/biz/regal-village-square-18-las-vegas ).
Archi's would be a good pre or post movie visit.
BTW, Archi's has been rated the Best of Las Vegas 2005-2007.

