I was looking for a Sprint store and remembered there being one near Ft Apache and Sahara, but I arrived too late and they were already closed.
So I decided to check out Rising Sun Sushi, which is supposedly located in the same strip mall (sign is still up), but after driving around the entire strip mall and not seeing any sign of Rising Sun and finding Archi's Thai Cafe next to the movie theater I decided to check out their dinner menu.
The restaurant itself looks nice, the dining area is split into 2 sections (at least), as I was directed to a corner table in the smaller more secluded dining section closest to the parking lot.
I was hoping to be seated in the main area, but whatever.
They have a few waitresses and 1 waiter, and I am not sure if they take turns in getting customers/tables, but I ended up with the waiter that still have a lot to learn about getting better at being a waitperson in a restaurant.
If the number of guestcheck holders in their apron is a direct count of the number of tables they are currently assigned, then I would say he has 3 tables to look after while I was there, and he was overwhelmed with just those 3 tables.
After I ordered and the food was served (by a different waitress), he did not come by to check up on the table until I was practically done eating, and it took forever (at least 5 minutes, but most likely not more than 10 minutes) to have him come by again to pick up the money.
This while at least 10 people were eying me sitting there waiting, while they wait for a table to be freed up so they can get seated and order some food.
Anyway, moving on to the food.
I have tried the curries before, and I thought about trying something new.
Sukiyaki (Thai Style) was what i ended up ordering, and I was thinking a Japanese Sukiyaki with Thai ingredients.
Completely wrong imagery!
What I ended up with was a bowl of Thai noodle soup that I remember eating at one of the street food vendors when I was a kid in Bangkok.
The flavor was the same as what I vaguely remembered.
It was served piping hot (good), with lots of vegetables (sure why not), a lot of pieces of chicken and 2 shrimps, plus a side of chili paste (cool, you can adjust how spicy you want).
But still I thought that item was overpriced for what it really is, and I will not order it again.
The Thai Iced Coffee is still large, and I think is worth the price of admission, and still very enjoyable.
I sometimes feel like just ordering that to go, if I am too lazy to shop at one of the Asian supermarket that sells them premade in cans or as a mix.
Overall: Service: 2/5 Food: 3.3/5 Price: 2/5 (For their Sukiyaki - Thai Style) Atmosphere: 4/5  This location is not recommended if you want to try Archi's and staying on the Strip, as their W. Flamingo location would be closer, and my experiences there have always been a good one.
But if you live near this location, by all means drop by and try any of their curries.

