So far, the best Thai food that I've tasted in Las Vegas.
That probably doesn't say much, as I've only been to one other Thai restaurant.
Came here around 6:30p on a Friday night.
There was a little bit of a wait, (20 minutes), but no big deal.
Started off with the Satay Chicken - nice and tender, and able to cut with a fork.
I didn't really care too much for the Thai Egg Rolls, not that it was bad or anything, but it was just an ordinary egg roll.
It did taste a little better with the peanut sauce from the Satay Chicken.
Got the Larb (spicy sausage salad).
My dining partner insisted on a spiciness level of 8, then after tasting it, proceeded to complain how it was too spicy - Lol!
I liked it, but it was a little sparse on the salad part.
Pad Kea Mow w/ chicken seemed to be a popular dish, so, we got that one too - it didn't disappoint.
Even though those were the only dishes we ordered, there was enough leftover for lunch the next day.
Service was good - server kept our water glasses full and frequently checked to see if everything was ok. On my next trip here, will try one of the curries, the spicy eggplant, and possibly the stuffed chicken wings.

The name Archi's doesn't scream Thai cuisine or anything Asian for that matter, but once you get passed the unusual name, this place is definitely one of the better Thai restaurants in Las Vegas (chain or otherwise).
Tom yum soup is delicious here and you can really judge a Thai restaurant from the quality of this traditional Thai soup.
The Lunch specials they have from 11 a.m. - 3 p.m. are a very good deal and equally as scrumptious!
Overall the interior of the restaurant is very pleasant and appealing for what it is and the menu prices are very reasonable.
If you like Thai food you should stop by here sometime!

